11:04.880 --> 11:06.870
(PHONE RINGING IN DISTANCE)

11:06.880 --> 11:08.880
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

11:33.320 --> 11:36.560
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

11:43.940 --> 11:46.270
INTERVIEWER: Modesto Cunanan.

11:46.280 --> 11:48.270
Please, everyone calls me Pete.

11:48.280 --> 11:49.300
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

11:49.310 --> 11:52.150
Frankly, uh, we don't
call in to interview

11:52.160 --> 11:56.060
many candidates like you,
at least not to be stockbrokers.

11:56.800 --> 11:58.710
- Like me?
- Uh, night-schooled.

11:58.720 --> 12:01.910
You've really pulled yourself up
by the bootstraps, haven't you?

12:02.140 --> 12:04.960
- Yes, sir.
- TEACHER: Andrew Cunanan?

12:07.000 --> 12:08.730
Right this way.

12:13.750 --> 12:16.540
MODESTO: <i> Gentlemen, I'm aware
that you have a long line</i>

12:16.550 --> 12:18.970
of eager Ivy League educated young men

12:18.980 --> 12:21.640
queuing up to be brokers
at Merrill Lynch,

12:22.130 --> 12:23.810
but ask yourself,

12:24.950 --> 12:26.960
how many of them started from nothing?

12:26.970 --> 12:29.440
Can you tell me why
you want to come to Bishop's?

12:29.450 --> 12:31.570
Because it's the best school
in California

12:31.580 --> 12:33.740
and one of the best schools in America.

12:33.750 --> 12:36.260
- Who told you that?
- My father.

12:36.270 --> 12:39.900
Mr. Cunanan, can we talk
a little more about business

12:39.920 --> 12:41.760
and a little less about your biography?

12:41.770 --> 12:44.730
But biography is business.

12:44.740 --> 12:48.360
My life is a tale told in dollars.

12:48.370 --> 12:51.830
I was born in Baliuag village,
the Philippines,

12:51.840 --> 12:54.830
in a house any of you gentlemen can buy

12:54.840 --> 12:57.500
with the money in your wallets.

12:57.510 --> 13:00.930
I served in the U.S. Navy
for $97 a month,

13:00.940 --> 13:02.350
not for the money,

13:02.360 --> 13:05.970
but for the opportunity to live and work

13:05.980 --> 13:08.470
in the United States of America,

13:08.480 --> 13:10.410
the greatest country in the world.

13:10.420 --> 13:13.080
- We thank you for your service.
- Yes, thank you.

13:13.100 --> 13:16.950
No, sir. I thank this country.
I thank it every day.

13:16.960 --> 13:20.790
Because after I arrived,
not far from the Navy docks,

13:20.800 --> 13:25.020
I bought my first home.
$12,000, it cost me.

13:25.030 --> 13:26.730
A few years later,

13:26.740 --> 13:31.010
I moved my family to an $80,000 home.

13:32.440 --> 13:36.050
Now, is that biography or business?

13:37.710 --> 13:39.770
Because I will tell your investors

13:39.780 --> 13:42.870
that's what I plan to do
with their money.

13:42.880 --> 13:47.050
I will cross oceans with it.
I will take it to new lands.

13:47.060 --> 13:51.020
I'm talking about growth
they can't imagine.

13:51.620 --> 13:55.120
TEACHER: <i> If you could have
one wish,</i> what would it be?

13:56.070 --> 13:58.260
A house overlooking the ocean,

13:58.940 --> 14:00.670
two Mercedes,

14:01.070 --> 14:05.030
four beautiful children,
three beautiful dogs,

14:05.040 --> 14:07.400
and a good relationship with God.

14:08.720 --> 14:10.700
Is that one wish or five?

14:10.710 --> 14:14.010
- Did I make a mistake?
- No, not at all.

14:14.020 --> 14:15.480
I'll ask it again.

14:16.050 --> 14:19.140
Andrew, if you could have one wish,

14:19.150 --> 14:22.550
just one wish,

14:22.560 --> 14:24.560
what would it be?

14:26.840 --> 14:28.520
To be special.

14:28.530 --> 14:30.700
- (DOOR OPENS)
- MARY ANNE: And then you must say...

14:30.710 --> 14:32.520
(MARY ANNE SPEAKS ITALIAN)

14:32.530 --> 14:34.030
(ANDREW REPEATS PHRASE IN ITALIAN)

14:34.040 --> 14:36.010
Oh, I'm so proud of you.

14:38.290 --> 14:39.410
Dad?

14:40.520 --> 14:42.530
I didn't get the job.

14:46.700 --> 14:48.190
They told you already?

14:48.760 --> 14:51.530
They called. It's a no.

14:57.790 --> 14:59.800
I'm so sorry.

15:03.930 --> 15:07.230
Only joking. I got the job.

15:07.240 --> 15:08.470
I'm in.

15:09.440 --> 15:11.030
At Merrill Lynch. (LAUGHS)

15:11.040 --> 15:13.430
- (MARY ANNE LAUGHS)
- The godfather of corporate America,

15:13.440 --> 15:14.730
and they want me!

15:14.740 --> 15:16.360
They want me!

15:16.370 --> 15:20.600
$60,000 starting salary,
and the sky's the limit.

15:21.330 --> 15:24.200
Tonight, we eat like kings.

15:24.210 --> 15:26.810
- (MARY ANNE GASPS) - From now on,
every night, we eat like kings.

15:26.820 --> 15:28.450
MARY ANNE: Oh! (LAUGHS)

15:28.460 --> 15:30.210
(MODESTO LAUGHS)

15:30.220 --> 15:33.460
- What's going on?
- Your father got the job!

15:35.460 --> 15:38.170
You didn't think I got it,
though, did you?

15:40.900 --> 15:43.460
Only because you said so.

15:43.470 --> 15:45.010
As a joke.

15:46.330 --> 15:48.440
Except you believed it.

15:49.490 --> 15:51.610
Quick to believe the worst?

15:55.480 --> 15:58.150
Modesto, I'm so happy.

16:04.580 --> 16:06.340
Andrew knew.

16:07.100 --> 16:10.540
He knew I got the job,
even before I said so.

16:11.670 --> 16:14.650
Maybe we should check
your medication again,

16:15.030 --> 16:17.820
see if your thoughts are confused.

16:18.640 --> 16:21.680
Don't want you going back
into the hospital.

16:23.710 --> 16:25.180
(MARY ANNE INHALES SHARPLY)

16:27.180 --> 16:28.820
Modesto.

16:31.420 --> 16:32.670
M...

16:36.280 --> 16:38.830
Let's celebrate! Hmm?

16:43.640 --> 16:45.520
Like kings.

16:46.170 --> 16:48.000
Just like you said.

16:56.340 --> 16:58.240
Move up. (SIGHS)

16:58.910 --> 17:00.250
Ah.

17:02.410 --> 17:05.200
Here. Where were we?

17:05.800 --> 17:08.150
"The Art of Conversation."

17:08.720 --> 17:10.710
Do we have to read the whole book?

17:11.430 --> 17:14.390
What is this, mutiny at bedtime?

17:15.140 --> 17:18.780
Yes, my son, who I love
more than I love my own life,

17:18.790 --> 17:20.660
we have to read the whole book,

17:20.670 --> 17:24.579
from "The Etiquette of Calling
Cards" to "Men's Apparel"

17:24.660 --> 17:26.730
to "Creating the Perfect Buffet Menu."

17:26.740 --> 17:28.569
You need to know it all.

17:28.580 --> 17:30.450
It's not enough to be smart.

17:30.460 --> 17:32.490
You need to fit in.

17:33.760 --> 17:35.600
Where were we?

17:35.960 --> 17:39.740
"There are two kinds of
CONVERSATION: polite and real."

17:39.750 --> 17:42.760
What happens if I don't get
accepted into Bishop's School?

17:44.590 --> 17:46.580
Don't be ridiculous.

17:46.590 --> 17:51.020
We moved to this house so you
could be close to that school.

17:51.030 --> 17:53.590
Of course you're going to get in.

17:54.210 --> 17:55.570
(MODESTO CHUCKLES)

17:56.580 --> 17:57.960
"Polite conversation."

17:57.970 --> 18:00.970
I like this. You could learn from this.

18:00.980 --> 18:02.980
♪ ♪

18:26.630 --> 18:28.640
♪ ♪

18:45.300 --> 18:49.260
Why are you crying? You got in.

19:03.700 --> 19:05.440
You...

19:06.730 --> 19:08.700
Oh!

19:08.920 --> 19:10.920
(LAUGHING)

19:23.170 --> 19:25.160
- (ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)
- (FRANTIC CHATTER)

19:26.630 --> 19:28.620
TRADER: ...I feel like I threw the ball

19:28.630 --> 19:30.490
- and caught the touchdown.
- (PHONES RINGING)

19:30.500 --> 19:33.700
Yeah. Oh, hey, I-I got to go.
400 shares.

19:33.710 --> 19:35.600
Hey, buddy!

19:35.610 --> 19:39.100
Hey. I hear you beat out 500 applicants.

19:39.110 --> 19:40.770
This trading floor is ruthless.

19:40.780 --> 19:43.000
You must be able to pull in
some mighty big numbers.

19:43.010 --> 19:44.840
This is you.

19:44.850 --> 19:47.640
- Let me show you how it's done.
- You got it. I like that.

19:47.650 --> 19:49.300
MODESTO: <i> Sir, I served</i>

19:49.340 --> 19:51.210
for seven years in the U.S. Navy,

19:51.220 --> 19:55.560
and nothing is more important to
me than integrity and honesty.

19:55.620 --> 19:58.620
But it's my duty... and, as a sailor,

19:58.630 --> 20:02.490
I never use that word lightly...
but it's my duty to point out

20:02.500 --> 20:04.790
that if you feel comfortable
about a stock,

20:04.800 --> 20:07.080
then it's probably a stock
everyone knows about.

20:07.180 --> 20:08.439
MAN (OVER PHONE):
You know, I see your point,

20:08.440 --> 20:10.770
but it's just not for me.
Thanks, anyway.

20:10.780 --> 20:12.780
- (LINE CLICKS)
- (DIAL TONE HUMMING)

20:17.280 --> 20:20.310
Yes, sir. I understand.

20:20.680 --> 20:23.940
But it's my job to find
exceptional opportunities.

20:23.960 --> 20:27.150
- And those are never, never
comfortable. -(LINE BEEPING)

20:27.160 --> 20:29.970
Do you want to be comfortable
or exceptional?

20:33.160 --> 20:34.960
That's what I want to hear, sir.

20:34.970 --> 20:36.190
(LAUGHS): Yes, sir.

20:37.070 --> 20:40.430
Now, to move this forward,
I'm gonna need a few details from you.

20:40.440 --> 20:42.660
Let's start with
your bank account number.

20:43.320 --> 20:44.930
MARY ANNE: Okay?

20:44.940 --> 20:47.080
And don't forget the comma.

20:47.790 --> 20:50.210
- Punctuation is the
music - (DOOR OPENS)

20:50.220 --> 20:52.170
- of language.
- MODESTO: Andrew.

20:52.180 --> 20:55.180
- I got something to show you.
- Not now. He's doing homework.

20:55.190 --> 20:57.360
That can wait. Come on.

21:01.270 --> 21:03.350
Close your eyes. There.

21:03.360 --> 21:05.350
- You excited?
- Uh-huh.

21:05.360 --> 21:07.190
- You want to see it?
- Yes.

21:07.200 --> 21:09.820
- You ready?
- Uh-huh.

21:09.830 --> 21:12.370
For you.

21:15.290 --> 21:16.960
I got the keys. You want it?

21:16.970 --> 21:18.270
Oh, too late.

21:18.280 --> 21:19.970
- (CHUCKLES)
- Try again.

21:19.980 --> 21:22.340
- Grab it like you mean it.
- (BOTH LAUGH)

21:22.350 --> 21:24.010
Just get in your car.

21:24.020 --> 21:26.440
(ANDREW CHUCKLES)

21:26.450 --> 21:28.460
Check it out.

21:30.280 --> 21:31.910
You bought a new car?

21:31.920 --> 21:34.820
- For Andrew.
- For Andrew?

21:34.830 --> 21:38.020
Don't say it like that.
I'm not an idiot.

21:38.610 --> 21:40.910
I know he can't drive yet,
but he can dream.

21:40.920 --> 21:42.240
You teach a boy how to dream.

21:42.260 --> 21:44.530
That's the most important lesson of all.

21:44.540 --> 21:47.040
You can't give him a a car.

21:52.110 --> 21:54.100
(QUIETLY): Stop it.

21:54.110 --> 21:57.110
Well... think of Elena.

21:57.120 --> 21:58.470
And Chris.

21:58.480 --> 22:01.340
They're actually old enough to drive.

22:01.350 --> 22:03.180
And a gift, for what?

22:03.190 --> 22:05.510
MODESTO: Have you gone mad again?

22:05.520 --> 22:07.350
He got into Bishop.

22:07.360 --> 22:09.890
But that's a beginning, not an end.

22:09.900 --> 22:11.150
(MARY ANNE GASPS)

22:11.160 --> 22:12.620
MODESTO: I'm just trying very hard

22:12.630 --> 22:15.520
to make sure
that he doesn't end up like you.

22:16.120 --> 22:17.490
(MARY ANNE GRUNTS)

22:20.500 --> 22:22.050
Don't overreact.

22:24.010 --> 22:25.100
Huh?

22:25.120 --> 22:27.540
You like it? (LAUGHS)

22:27.550 --> 22:29.200
Let's play.

22:29.210 --> 22:31.110
- Okay.
- Here we go.

22:31.120 --> 22:32.910
Put your hands on the wheel.

22:32.920 --> 22:35.150
Come on. Feel it. (PANTING)

22:40.930 --> 22:44.880
Your brothers and sisters, I love them.

22:46.380 --> 22:48.380
They're good kids.

22:49.900 --> 22:52.140
But they're not special.

22:54.420 --> 22:57.010
You're the best friend I ever had.

23:02.510 --> 23:05.600
Your mom was very sick
when you were born.

23:06.900 --> 23:08.440
Couldn't even get out of bed

23:08.450 --> 23:11.850
when she was in the hospital
with depression.

23:11.860 --> 23:13.860
Weak mind.

23:18.370 --> 23:20.940
It was me who looked after you.

23:21.970 --> 23:24.840
I was your mother and your father.

23:34.210 --> 23:37.540
- (RADIO STATIC CRACKLES)
- (STATIONS CHANGING)

23:37.550 --> 23:40.550
(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING OVER RADIO)

24:00.830 --> 24:02.310
Dad?

24:02.960 --> 24:04.200
Yes?

24:04.690 --> 24:07.690
Did you always want to be a stockbroker?

24:09.550 --> 24:11.750
I, uh, followed

24:11.760 --> 24:14.760
whatever opportunities came my way.

24:16.560 --> 24:19.310
I'm the world's greatest opportunist.

24:19.320 --> 24:22.350
Pure and simple.

24:22.360 --> 24:26.990
That's the only way
to survive in this world.

24:27.000 --> 24:30.660
I like reading and stories.

24:30.670 --> 24:33.270
Maybe I could write books.

24:37.530 --> 24:41.440
Somebody offers you a million dollars
to write a book...

24:42.370 --> 24:43.960
sure, take it.

24:43.970 --> 24:45.570
Why not?

24:47.080 --> 24:51.420
Otherwise... no.

25:01.810 --> 25:06.090
Did I ever tell you about how,
when you were a little boy,

25:07.090 --> 25:11.210
you burnt your foot on a heater?

25:12.940 --> 25:14.960
I picked you up.

25:15.760 --> 25:17.780
Kissed you better.

25:19.030 --> 25:21.290
And you didn't make a sound.

25:25.450 --> 25:27.050
Not a sound.

25:28.030 --> 25:29.370
(LIGHT SWITCH CLICKS)

25:35.190 --> 25:38.680
♪ Time, time, time ♪

25:39.260 --> 25:44.100
♪ See what's become of me ♪

25:48.530 --> 25:50.230
♪ ♪

25:59.700 --> 26:01.710
(TIRES SCREECH)

26:02.950 --> 26:05.240
♪ Time, time, time ♪

26:05.250 --> 26:08.370
♪ See what's become of me ♪

26:08.380 --> 26:11.320
♪ While I looked around ♪

26:11.500 --> 26:15.050
♪ For my possibilities ♪

26:15.060 --> 26:18.050
♪ I was so hard to please ♪

26:18.620 --> 26:19.850
♪ Look around ♪

26:19.860 --> 26:21.520
♪ Leaves are brown ♪

26:21.530 --> 26:23.110
♪ And the sky ♪

26:23.120 --> 26:26.760
♪ Is a hazy shade of winter ♪

26:27.130 --> 26:31.660
♪ Hear the Salvation Army band ♪

26:31.670 --> 26:33.030
♪ Down by the riverside ♪

26:33.040 --> 26:34.960
♪ It's bound to be a better ride ♪

26:34.970 --> 26:37.470
♪ Than what you've got planned ♪

26:37.480 --> 26:40.840
♪ Carry a cup in your hand ♪

26:40.850 --> 26:42.510
♪ Look around ♪

26:42.520 --> 26:43.840
♪ Grass is high ♪

26:43.850 --> 26:45.410
♪ Fields are ripe ♪

26:45.420 --> 26:47.740
♪ It's the springtime of my life. ♪

26:48.610 --> 26:50.410
What are we?

26:51.390 --> 26:52.870
Are we sheep?

26:52.880 --> 26:54.590
We all have to do the same thing?

26:54.600 --> 26:56.490
Stand the same way?

26:56.500 --> 26:57.990
Smile the same smile?

26:58.000 --> 26:59.940
(ITALIAN ACCENT):
Where's our sense of rebellion?

26:59.950 --> 27:02.450
Shut up. Fag.

27:07.410 --> 27:10.110
(NORMAL VOICE): If being a fag
means being different...

27:13.610 --> 27:15.670
...sign me up!

27:15.680 --> 27:18.590
Take a photograph, my good man.

27:26.140 --> 27:28.130
♪ ♪

27:41.110 --> 27:43.110
(QUIET CHATTER)

27:45.780 --> 27:47.770
(TOILET FLUSHES)

27:47.780 --> 27:49.770
(PHONES RINGING)

27:49.780 --> 27:51.790
(PRINTER WHIRRING)

27:55.550 --> 27:57.550
♪ ♪

28:17.290 --> 28:19.750
Vera, hello. It's Pete. Pete Cunanan.

28:19.760 --> 28:23.390
(CHUCKLES) Of course I called back.
I promised I would.

28:23.400 --> 28:27.180
Listen, I know
our last trade didn't work out.

28:27.190 --> 28:28.980
World events overtook us.

28:29.190 --> 28:31.830
But I have a new opportunity

28:31.840 --> 28:35.540
that will make all our money
back, and so much more.

28:35.710 --> 28:38.370
You'll be so rich, you'll never
worry about money again.

28:38.380 --> 28:41.240
But I see here that we need to liquidate

28:41.250 --> 28:43.480
your late husband's
pension to make our move.

28:43.490 --> 28:45.630
- Hey, Grandma.
- I know, it does sound scary,

28:45.640 --> 28:48.230
- but it's my duty to point out...
- MAN: Who are you talking to?

28:48.240 --> 28:51.330
that if you feel comfortable about a
stock, then it's probably a stock

28:51.340 --> 28:53.190
- everyone knows about.
- MAN: Is that the man?

28:53.200 --> 28:55.320
We need to act fast,
so I'm gonna need a...

28:55.330 --> 28:57.920
MAN: My grandma is 90 years old.

28:57.930 --> 29:01.760
And when you steal her money,
she can't heat her house.

29:02.410 --> 29:05.410
I'm gonna hunt you down,
you son of a bitch.

29:06.810 --> 29:08.810
♪ ♪

29:25.590 --> 29:27.320
MARY ANNE: So...

29:28.300 --> 29:31.460
when do I get to meet this special lady?

29:32.460 --> 29:34.270
I'm not a fool.

29:34.280 --> 29:36.460
I know there's someone.

29:37.020 --> 29:39.580
You don't smell this nice for me.

29:41.120 --> 29:43.120
Hmm?

29:46.780 --> 29:49.940
What if I told you...

29:49.950 --> 29:52.520
she was older than 30?

29:55.990 --> 29:58.100
I would say

29:59.040 --> 30:02.990
a young man should always be
with an older woman.

30:04.180 --> 30:06.900
She teaches him how to be a man.

30:08.800 --> 30:10.650
How did you meet?

30:12.150 --> 30:13.550
Babysitting.

30:19.350 --> 30:21.640
- ♪ This is the night ♪
- ♪<i> Yeah</i> ♪

30:21.650 --> 30:23.780
♪ This is the night ♪

30:23.790 --> 30:25.940
♪ This is the time ♪

30:25.950 --> 30:28.880
- ♪ We've got to get it right ♪
- ♪<i> This is the night</i> ♪

30:28.890 --> 30:30.980
♪ Touch me, touch me ♪

30:30.990 --> 30:33.450
♪ I wanna feel your body ♪

30:33.460 --> 30:37.860
- ♪ Your heartbeat next to mine ♪
- ♪<i> This is the night</i> ♪

30:37.870 --> 30:40.470
♪ Touch me, touch me now ♪

30:42.700 --> 30:45.470
♪ Touch me, touch me now ♪

30:47.010 --> 30:49.030
♪ Touch me, touch me ♪

30:49.040 --> 30:53.380
♪ Now. ♪

31:11.070 --> 31:13.070
(DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE)

31:23.170 --> 31:26.170
- What are you wearing?
- Ah, no peeking.

31:27.100 --> 31:29.010
Glove compartment.

31:30.180 --> 31:31.890
(GLOVE COMPARTMENT OPENS)

31:33.190 --> 31:34.720
ANDREW: Oh.

31:37.770 --> 31:39.770
It's nice.

31:44.770 --> 31:46.730
Wait, wait.

31:47.540 --> 31:50.410
I-I want to make something clear.

31:51.440 --> 31:53.530
I know you buy me gifts,

31:53.540 --> 31:56.630
but that's not
what this is about for me.

31:56.640 --> 31:59.370
Andrew, easy.

32:00.550 --> 32:03.110
Don't get so serious.

32:04.460 --> 32:06.610
So, where are we going?

32:07.220 --> 32:09.450
It's a surprise.

32:09.460 --> 32:11.790
- (POP MUSIC PLAYING INSIDE)
- (LIVELY CHATTER)

32:13.800 --> 32:16.120
This is your surprise?

32:16.700 --> 32:19.060
- A house party?
- Why not? It'll be fun.

32:19.070 --> 32:21.490
What, are you out of your mind?

32:21.500 --> 32:24.830
I'm married. We're a secret.

32:24.840 --> 32:28.510
I don't want us to be a secret anymore.

32:28.520 --> 32:32.040
This is strictly on the side.

32:33.510 --> 32:36.470
What? You thought it could be more?

32:36.480 --> 32:37.980
(POUNDING ON CAR)

32:37.990 --> 32:40.410
(LAUGHTER)

32:45.110 --> 32:46.370
Get out.

32:48.500 --> 32:49.880
Now.

32:56.870 --> 32:59.200
("WHIP IT" BY DEVO PLAYING)

32:59.210 --> 33:01.210
(TIRES SCREECH)

33:09.520 --> 33:12.680
♪ Crack that whip ♪

33:12.690 --> 33:15.650
♪ Give the past the slip ♪

33:15.660 --> 33:18.680
♪ Step on a crack ♪

33:18.690 --> 33:20.830
♪ Break your mama's back ♪

33:22.860 --> 33:24.790
♪ When a problem comes along ♪

33:24.800 --> 33:26.220
♪ You must whip it ♪

33:26.230 --> 33:27.890
♪ Before the cream sits out too long ♪

33:27.900 --> 33:29.610
♪ You must whip it ♪

33:29.620 --> 33:31.000
♪ When something's going wrong ♪

33:31.010 --> 33:32.230
♪ You must whip it... ♪

33:32.240 --> 33:33.800
JEROME: I'm gonna do it.

33:33.810 --> 33:35.390
I'm gonna ask Andrew out. How do I look?

33:35.400 --> 33:36.830
- You look great.
- Too tidy?

33:36.840 --> 33:38.540
I'm always too tidy. I can't do scruffy.

33:38.550 --> 33:40.870
♪ Go forward ♪

33:40.880 --> 33:42.310
♪ Move ahead ♪

33:42.320 --> 33:43.710
♪ Try to detect it ♪

33:43.720 --> 33:44.880
♪ It's not too late ♪

33:44.890 --> 33:47.050
♪ To whip it ♪

33:47.060 --> 33:50.220
♪ Whip it good ♪

33:50.230 --> 33:52.080
♪ When a good time turns around ♪

33:52.090 --> 33:53.550
♪ You must whip it ♪

33:53.560 --> 33:55.360
♪ You will never live it down ♪

33:55.380 --> 33:56.540
♪ Unless you whip it ♪

33:56.840 --> 33:58.020
♪ No one gets away ♪

33:58.030 --> 33:59.570
♪ Until they whip it ♪

34:01.570 --> 34:04.660
♪ I say whip it ♪

34:04.670 --> 34:07.930
♪ Whip it good ♪

34:07.940 --> 34:10.699
♪ I say whip it ♪

34:10.710 --> 34:12.719
♪ Whip it good ♪

34:23.090 --> 34:25.250
You look fabulous.

34:25.260 --> 34:28.090
Oh, what, this thing? This little thing?

34:28.100 --> 34:30.850
- (LAUGHS)
- ♪ Crack that whip ♪

34:30.860 --> 34:33.260
♪ Give the past the slip. ♪

34:34.409 --> 34:36.219
Red is my favorite color.

34:36.230 --> 34:37.760
Silver is mine.

34:37.770 --> 34:40.130
(GASPS) We should do a clothes swap.

34:41.500 --> 34:44.770
Oh, my God. Oh, my God!
You actually would do it.

34:44.780 --> 34:48.110
I know for a fact
that you don't go to Bishop's,

34:48.120 --> 34:51.639
because if you did,
I think we'd be best friends.

34:51.650 --> 34:52.639
Oh, now you made me sad.

34:52.659 --> 34:55.039
- Did I miss our chance to be friends?
- No.

34:55.040 --> 34:56.780
Our time is now.

34:56.790 --> 34:58.120
I'm Andrew.

34:58.130 --> 35:00.050
I'm Lizzie.

35:00.060 --> 35:01.920
- Hi, Lizzie.
- Hi.

35:01.930 --> 35:06.220
Um, can I tell you a secret?

35:06.230 --> 35:09.290
Can we only ever speak in secrets?

35:09.300 --> 35:11.670
I'm an imposter.

35:13.740 --> 35:15.630
(WHISPERS): All the best people are.

35:15.640 --> 35:17.640
Um, I'm... oh.

35:17.650 --> 35:19.900
I'm actually married.

35:19.910 --> 35:24.910
And I have a big, boring house
with a big... (CHUCKLES)

35:24.920 --> 35:26.340
boring husband.

35:26.350 --> 35:30.320
And we are friends with
the DeSilvas who own this house,

35:30.330 --> 35:33.990
and they've asked me
to keep an eye on it.

35:34.000 --> 35:37.990
Are you what is commonly known
as a grown-up?

35:38.000 --> 35:40.660
Why? Does that mean
you won't talk to me anymore?

35:40.670 --> 35:42.990
No. On the contrary,
I get along so much better

35:43.000 --> 35:44.830
with people that aren't my own age.

35:44.840 --> 35:46.160
Good.

35:46.180 --> 35:48.430
Because... I sort of...

35:48.440 --> 35:50.870
I sort of missed all of this, you know.

35:50.880 --> 35:53.170
What, all this?

35:53.180 --> 35:56.940
Youth and fun. Silliness.

35:56.950 --> 35:58.110
Why?

35:58.120 --> 36:00.850
I was homeschooled. Isn't that pitiful?

36:00.860 --> 36:02.660
No, I can't wait to get out of school.

36:02.700 --> 36:04.880
Why? What do you want to do?

36:04.890 --> 36:06.800
(ANDREW SIGHS)

36:08.800 --> 36:12.720
I want to seek out my heroes.

36:12.730 --> 36:16.690
Basquiat, Mapplethorpe, Patti Smith.

36:16.700 --> 36:19.200
Herb Ritts. Keith Haring.

36:19.210 --> 36:21.730
- Versace.
- Yeah.

36:21.740 --> 36:23.710
- Yeah. Yeah.
- (LIZZIE LAUGHS)

36:32.280 --> 36:34.280
- (QUIET CHATTER)
- (TV PLAYING QUIETLY)

36:34.290 --> 36:36.290
(PHONES RINGING)

36:41.150 --> 36:43.450
They're waiting for you.

37:02.410 --> 37:06.110
Pete, have a seat.

37:06.120 --> 37:08.620
This is a surprise, gentlemen.

37:09.690 --> 37:11.890
Am I being promoted?

37:12.840 --> 37:16.900
Have you ever traded
in nonexistent stocks?

37:17.520 --> 37:20.170
No. Never.

37:20.180 --> 37:22.400
A man has accused you
of tricking his grandmother

37:22.410 --> 37:23.900
into handing over her life savings.

37:23.910 --> 37:27.740
- Over $25,000.
- She's 92 years old.

37:29.820 --> 37:34.820
She made a trade, high risk,
high reward. It didn't work out.

37:35.430 --> 37:36.870
What can I say?

37:36.980 --> 37:39.570
If the stocks weren't real,
it's not only unethical,

37:39.580 --> 37:40.920
it's illegal.

37:41.590 --> 37:43.380
You got this all wrong.

37:44.170 --> 37:46.420
Let me make some calls.

37:46.430 --> 37:48.280
There's been a misunderstanding.

37:48.290 --> 37:51.160
How many misunderstandings
have there been over the years?

37:51.170 --> 37:53.140
Why have you changed jobs so frequently?

37:53.150 --> 37:57.410
No one voluntarily chooses
to go from Merrill to us.

37:59.160 --> 38:01.840
I wanted to spend more time
with my family.

38:01.850 --> 38:03.840
The feds are involved now.

38:03.850 --> 38:07.050
They're going over
your entire employment history.

38:08.000 --> 38:09.770
We're cooperating fully.

38:10.160 --> 38:12.120
We have nothing to hide.

38:13.200 --> 38:15.370
Do you have anything to hide, Pete?

38:17.400 --> 38:19.030
No.

38:20.370 --> 38:22.370
I have nothing to hide.

38:24.020 --> 38:25.630
(DOOR OPENS)

38:27.910 --> 38:29.910
♪ ♪

38:40.890 --> 38:42.890
- (SHREDDER WHIRRING)
- (FLOPPY DISK SNAPS)

38:48.900 --> 38:50.670
(SHREDDER BEEPS, STOPS)

38:54.900 --> 38:56.910
♪ ♪

39:10.040 --> 39:11.690
(SIGHS)

39:29.940 --> 39:32.930
(LINE RINGS, CLICKS)

39:32.940 --> 39:35.230
Jenny. Pete Cunanan.

39:35.240 --> 39:38.580
I need to book that flight, for today.

39:40.280 --> 39:41.950
(TIRES SCREECH)

39:50.960 --> 39:53.800
FBI. We have a warrant
for Modesto Cunanan.

39:53.960 --> 39:55.250
(PHONE RINGS)

39:55.260 --> 39:57.260
RECEPTIONIST (OVER PHONE): Get out now.

40:06.640 --> 40:08.980
- Back corner office.
- Back corner.

40:19.920 --> 40:22.730
Well, you got
Most Likely to Be Remembered.

40:25.000 --> 40:27.270
Andrew, no one cares
about the yearbook awards.

40:27.280 --> 40:29.250
Says the man that didn't get one.

40:30.670 --> 40:32.620
STUDENT: "Apres moi, Le deluge"?

40:32.630 --> 40:35.300
"After me, destruction."

40:37.130 --> 40:39.340
I don't know, sounded kind of cool.

40:45.180 --> 40:46.520
(TIRES SCREECH)

40:56.910 --> 40:58.020
Andrew?

40:58.030 --> 41:00.030
♪ ♪

41:16.720 --> 41:17.940
Modesto.

41:17.960 --> 41:19.550
What's happening?

41:19.560 --> 41:22.800
What is that? (GASPS)

41:26.270 --> 41:27.430
(LOUD KNOCK ON DOOR)

41:27.440 --> 41:30.500
Modesto Cunanan,
this is the FBI. Open up.

41:30.760 --> 41:33.820
- (POUNDING ON DOOR)
- Open up.

41:33.830 --> 41:36.120
We have a warrant for your arrest.

41:38.700 --> 41:40.700
♪ ♪

42:01.090 --> 42:03.080
- FBI.
- (POUNDING ON DOOR)

42:03.970 --> 42:05.860
Where is he?

42:13.910 --> 42:15.290
Dad...

42:19.630 --> 42:22.000
Don't believe a word they say.

42:28.320 --> 42:30.880
(CAR DOOR OPENS, CLOSES)

42:30.890 --> 42:33.750
(ENGINE STARTS, REVS)

42:33.760 --> 42:35.760
(TIRES SCREECHING)

42:50.160 --> 42:52.900
MARY ANNE: <i>
The credit cards are maxed out.</i>

42:53.760 --> 42:56.190
He emptied the bank accounts.

42:57.290 --> 42:59.530
He transferred all the money.

43:00.150 --> 43:04.150
This house? He sold it weeks ago.

43:05.910 --> 43:07.590
He knew.

43:08.490 --> 43:10.630
He knew they were coming.

43:11.730 --> 43:13.790
We have nowhere to live.

43:14.700 --> 43:16.670
We have nothing.

43:19.800 --> 43:21.800
♪ ♪

43:46.090 --> 43:47.920
Where are you going?

43:49.660 --> 43:52.720
- To find Dad.
- Andrew, he's gone.

43:53.490 --> 43:55.270
He left us.

43:55.280 --> 43:57.170
He left the country.

43:57.200 --> 44:00.670
He fled to Manila like a dirty rat.

44:00.680 --> 44:02.900
He is a thief and a liar!

44:02.910 --> 44:06.130
(CRYING): I knew it
and I kept my mouth shut.

44:07.540 --> 44:09.700
I should've said something.

44:11.020 --> 44:12.800
Andrew.

44:14.010 --> 44:16.350
Please forgive me. Forg...

44:16.580 --> 44:18.030
_

44:21.630 --> 44:23.440
_

44:24.000 --> 44:27.820
No. There is no plan.

44:27.830 --> 44:29.730
He doesn't have a plan.

44:29.740 --> 44:31.790
He doesn't have a dollar to his name.

44:31.800 --> 44:32.930
He wouldn't leave us with nothing, Mom.

44:32.940 --> 44:34.400
- That's not how... that's not like him.
- He did.

44:34.420 --> 44:38.100
He left us with nothing
and I am begging you don't go!

44:38.110 --> 44:41.930
I'm scared. He's dangerous!

44:47.260 --> 44:49.290
You're wrong about him.

44:51.260 --> 44:53.170
You're wrong.

44:54.260 --> 44:55.700
(BAG ZIPS)

45:04.000 --> 45:06.500
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)
- (HORNS HONKING)

45:06.880 --> 45:08.570
CAB DRIVER: Hey, boss, skipper.

45:08.580 --> 45:10.350
Uh, sir, I'm open, I'm open.

45:10.360 --> 45:12.040
(GRUNTS)

45:12.470 --> 45:15.420
I'm going to Baliu... Baliuag. Baliuag?

45:15.430 --> 45:18.210
Uh, I need to go to this address.

45:19.770 --> 45:21.600
Ah. Baliuag.

45:21.610 --> 45:24.100
Uh, you sure you want to go here?

45:24.110 --> 45:26.970
I know a nice hotel. MTV, minibar.

45:26.980 --> 45:30.940
No, I-I need, I need
to go to that... that place.

45:31.450 --> 45:33.490
<i>Sí.</i> Baliuag.

45:40.960 --> 45:42.960
♪ ♪

46:14.020 --> 46:16.010
Th-This is it?

46:16.030 --> 46:18.030
This is it.

46:32.850 --> 46:34.840
(INSECTS CHIRPING)

46:34.850 --> 46:36.850
♪ ♪

46:44.890 --> 46:47.720
(DOGS BARKING, SNARLING)

46:47.730 --> 46:49.950
Oi! Shh, shh. Hey.

46:49.960 --> 46:52.200
(DOOR CLOSES)

46:56.140 --> 46:57.700
(SPEAKS TAGALOG)

46:58.140 --> 47:01.540
Hello. Uh... I'm Andrew.

47:03.450 --> 47:06.300
I'm Modesto's son. Are you his brother?

47:06.310 --> 47:10.110
<i>¿Cómo está, Andrew?</i> Huh?

47:10.120 --> 47:12.540
Welcome, welcome.

47:12.550 --> 47:14.910
Call me Tito, huh?

47:14.920 --> 47:18.710
Sorry, but I-I do not speak,
uh, much English.

47:18.720 --> 47:21.690
- Do you speak Tagalog?
- No. No, I'm sorry.

47:21.700 --> 47:25.030
Ah. Is this your, uh, first time home?

47:28.570 --> 47:31.730
- Is my father here?
- Ah. Okay. Come, come.

47:31.740 --> 47:33.570
He's here. (SPEAKS TAGALOG)

47:37.080 --> 47:39.080
TITO: Be careful of the water.

47:51.590 --> 47:52.980
He's here.

47:56.200 --> 47:59.730
- In there?
- (SPEAKS TAGALOG)

48:12.610 --> 48:14.620
♪ ♪

48:27.630 --> 48:29.630
(DOOR CREAKS)

48:51.150 --> 48:53.150
♪ ♪

49:09.940 --> 49:12.160
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

49:12.170 --> 49:13.870
(LAUGHS)

49:15.930 --> 49:18.170
I knew you'd come.

49:18.180 --> 49:20.000
(LAUGHS)

49:20.720 --> 49:22.720
(SIGHS): Oh.

49:27.260 --> 49:29.180
Chicharrón.

49:29.190 --> 49:30.810
Pork skin.

49:31.340 --> 49:34.780
It don't look pretty,
but with a cold beer...

49:34.790 --> 49:36.800
(CHUCKLES)

49:44.600 --> 49:46.470
Long flight.

49:56.920 --> 50:00.080
You have questions.

50:00.650 --> 50:02.600
Mom says there's no money.

50:03.480 --> 50:05.740
Your mother has a weak mind.

50:07.300 --> 50:10.120
(SCOFFS) She always had a weak mind.

50:10.130 --> 50:13.620
- You sold the house.
- Otherwise, they would have taken it.

50:13.630 --> 50:16.230
I needed to move everything
out of reach.

50:16.240 --> 50:20.630
So... there's money?

50:20.640 --> 50:22.780
Millions.

50:24.010 --> 50:25.710
I would say.

50:26.890 --> 50:28.490
Where?

50:31.600 --> 50:32.980
I told you.

50:34.400 --> 50:35.650
Did you?

50:36.250 --> 50:37.990
Out of reach.

50:41.950 --> 50:43.270
Oh.

50:43.760 --> 50:45.090
(CHUCKLES)

50:45.100 --> 50:47.870
I'm so happy you're here.

50:51.170 --> 50:53.670
- (THUNDER RUMBLING SOFTLY)
- (RAIN FALLING)

51:24.240 --> 51:27.130
(EXHALES)

51:27.140 --> 51:29.210
Can't sleep?

51:30.710 --> 51:32.710
I'm not surprised.

51:33.710 --> 51:35.720
It's the heat.

51:38.720 --> 51:40.650
Me, I'm used to it.

51:42.260 --> 51:43.840
Grew up in it.

51:44.260 --> 51:48.230
Played in it. Worked in it.

51:50.900 --> 51:53.340
It's been a while
since I've been back, but...

51:54.070 --> 51:56.070
the body remembers.

51:59.070 --> 52:02.390
You can pretend
you belong somewhere else,

52:03.460 --> 52:05.460
but the body knows.

52:07.010 --> 52:09.250
There's no money, is there?

52:12.020 --> 52:13.640
No.

52:15.720 --> 52:17.420
No plan.

52:19.060 --> 52:22.940
No... millions.

52:24.160 --> 52:27.290
You watch your tone with me, young man.

52:27.300 --> 52:30.870
- I'm still your father.
- My father.

52:33.910 --> 52:35.440
My father.

52:37.150 --> 52:39.490
He's a liar.

52:41.450 --> 52:43.810
My father's a thief.

52:43.820 --> 52:46.380
You judge me, boy?

52:47.860 --> 52:50.210
You want to know what my crime was?

52:50.220 --> 52:53.280
Not that I stole; they're all stealing.

52:53.290 --> 52:56.550
No, my crime was that I stole too small.

52:56.560 --> 52:59.960
A thousand dollars here,
a few thousand dollars there.

52:59.970 --> 53:02.010
That was my mistake.

53:04.020 --> 53:06.060
So I admit it, yes.

53:06.070 --> 53:07.800
I stole.

53:07.810 --> 53:11.130
But only what I needed to be a father.

53:11.140 --> 53:14.300
Only what I needed to be an American.

53:14.310 --> 53:18.410
You can't go to America and start
from nothing. That's the lie.

53:20.090 --> 53:21.990
So I stole.

53:25.160 --> 53:27.580
If I had stolen a hundred million,

53:27.590 --> 53:30.600
they would have promoted me.

53:35.600 --> 53:38.210
I can't be this.

53:39.990 --> 53:41.980
What? What can't you be?

53:42.000 --> 53:43.480
I can't be you.

53:44.840 --> 53:46.200
Me?

53:47.480 --> 53:49.980
What, I'm not good enough for you now?

53:53.320 --> 53:56.960
I brag to my friends about your success.

53:59.760 --> 54:02.350
You were everything to me, Dad.

54:03.290 --> 54:04.350
But it's a lie.

54:04.360 --> 54:06.360
And if you're a lie,

54:06.370 --> 54:09.340
then I'm a lie,
and I-I can't be a lie. I can't.

54:19.880 --> 54:22.880
You know, before I came here...

54:26.050 --> 54:28.170
...I went to the library.

54:29.320 --> 54:31.210
To read up on Manila.

54:31.220 --> 54:35.220
And while I was there,
I thought, "I'll look up Dad

54:35.230 --> 54:39.260
in <i> California's Top 500 Stockbrokers."</i>

54:40.500 --> 54:43.900
Because I wanted to see
what they said about my father.

54:45.910 --> 54:49.430
The library didn't have a copy,

54:49.440 --> 54:52.000
- because...
- (CHOPPING)

54:52.010 --> 54:54.240
it doesn't exist.

54:54.250 --> 54:57.380
It's not real. It never existed, Dad.

55:04.690 --> 55:06.640
Are you crying?

55:07.530 --> 55:09.130
(ANDREW SNIFFLES)

55:12.810 --> 55:14.560
Weak.

55:15.270 --> 55:17.270
Just like your mother.

55:20.040 --> 55:23.030
The two of you talk about honesty.

55:23.040 --> 55:27.280
But she never cared that I was stealing,
as long as there was money.

55:28.310 --> 55:31.260
Why didn't you ask
about the book before?

55:31.950 --> 55:34.210
Because there was money.

55:34.220 --> 55:39.290
You're not upset that I stole,
you're upset because I stopped!

55:39.840 --> 55:43.390
Now you have to work. For yourself.

55:43.400 --> 55:46.460
You sissy kid with a sissy mind!

55:46.470 --> 55:47.750
(SPITS)

55:49.890 --> 55:52.470
You think you can come here, judge me,

55:52.480 --> 55:53.960
and tell me that I'm nothing?

55:53.970 --> 55:57.130
No, no, boy, I judge you!

55:57.140 --> 56:00.640
I spit on you! I'm ashamed of you!

56:00.650 --> 56:03.450
My special sissy boy!

56:04.550 --> 56:07.280
You couldn't even get
from one street to another,

56:07.290 --> 56:09.580
let alone from Manila to America.

56:09.590 --> 56:11.160
And back again.

56:15.160 --> 56:18.000
♪ ♪

56:24.630 --> 56:26.110
Do it.

56:28.210 --> 56:30.430
Be a man!

56:30.440 --> 56:32.450
For once!

56:36.180 --> 56:37.290
No?

56:45.540 --> 56:46.830
No.

56:47.460 --> 56:49.630
(CRYING)

56:51.500 --> 56:54.470
You don't have it in you.

57:07.550 --> 57:10.190
(QUIETLY): I'll never be like you.

57:27.030 --> 57:29.030
♪ ♪

57:35.940 --> 57:37.940
(INDISTINCT POLICE RADIO CHATTER)

57:39.310 --> 57:42.570
(CAR DOOR OPENS, CLOSES)

57:42.740 --> 57:45.230
(ENGINE STARTS)

57:45.240 --> 57:47.170
MAN: Such a shame.

57:51.100 --> 57:53.940
Oh, God. Be careful with those.

57:53.950 --> 57:55.100
Andrew.

57:55.110 --> 57:57.240
Andrew, you're back.

57:57.250 --> 57:58.420
Andrew?

58:03.620 --> 58:05.630
♪ ♪

58:31.050 --> 58:33.050
(SHOUTING)

58:51.240 --> 58:53.240
(CRICKETS CHIRPING)

59:05.890 --> 59:08.390
(DOOR BELLS JINGLE)

59:08.400 --> 59:10.530
MR. MERCADO: ...and you have my number,

59:10.540 --> 59:13.070
if anything comes up in the meantime.

59:13.080 --> 59:15.080
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS)

59:17.710 --> 59:19.040
How can I help you?

59:19.050 --> 59:21.550
I saw the-the "help wanted" sign.

59:21.560 --> 59:22.860
Ah.

59:26.440 --> 59:27.900
Here you go.

59:34.650 --> 59:36.650
Are you Filipino?

59:38.250 --> 59:39.890
On my father's side.

59:39.900 --> 59:42.470
What's his name?
I'm sure I've seen him around.

59:45.440 --> 59:47.490
My mom does all the shopping.

59:48.830 --> 59:50.610
What does your dad do?

59:51.160 --> 59:53.700
He lives in Manila now.

59:53.710 --> 59:56.250
My family comes from Manila.

59:58.650 --> 01:00:00.130
Great.

01:00:00.680 --> 01:00:02.070
Do you visit him often?

01:00:02.080 --> 01:00:04.400
I've just come back from visiting him.

01:00:04.980 --> 01:00:07.050
Ah. What's he up to there?

01:00:10.950 --> 01:00:15.220
Uh, he owns multiple
pineapple plantations.

01:00:18.230 --> 01:00:19.570
Is that so?

01:00:20.060 --> 01:00:22.250
As far as the eye can see.

